ABUJA – A presidential aspirant for 2023 and media mogul, Dumebi Kachikwu has described Senate rejection of the Electoral Act Bill as a “bold and heroic act.” Congratulating the Senate for its courage and patriotism in thrash­ing a Bill seeking to amend the Electoral Act 2022, Kachikwu who is the Chairman of Roots Television Nigeria, added that political appoin­tees seeking to contest political positions should first resign their appointments before partaking in primaries. Kachikwu, in a statement in Abuja stated: “The Senate de­serves the commendation of all for rejecting a Bill seeking to expunge Section 84 (12) of the Electoral Act, 2022, which bars appointed politi­cal office holders from contesting elective political positions without first resigning their appointments. APC: Members Plan Heroic Welcome For CECPC Buni IWD: SWAN Urges NASS To Revisit Gender Bills “Nobody can eat his cake and have it. Therefore, let political appointees seeking to contest po­litical positions first resign their appointments before partaking in primaries. “I think this is fair, just and equi­table. Let all aspirants seeking polit­ical offices be on the same footing. “This bold and heroic act by the Senate will ensure that political appointees seeking elective offices will not use government resources at their disposal to stifle or muzzle the chances of other aspirants. “The era of using national re­sources to procure elective posi­tions is gone for good.” Recall that President Muham­madu Buhari had in a letter to the upper chamber on 25th February 2022, requested the lawmakers to expunge section 84(12) of the Elec­toral Act.